<ArticleLayout
  title="Kitchen Storage: What to Measure and Check Before You Buy"
  description="Before buying kitchen storage, check the space, layout, rental limits, cleaning needs and daily habits that affect whether organisers, containers and shelves will actually help."
  category="Kitchen"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="10 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/kitchen.webp"
  imageAlt="A warm kitchen with timber cabinetry, green accents and a tidy benchtop"
>
  <p>
    Kitchen storage problems are rarely just about not having enough cupboards. In many
    Australian homes, the real issue is a mix of awkward shelves, deep pantry spaces,
    mismatched containers, bulky appliances, narrow drawers, rental restrictions and everyday
    habits that make the kitchen harder to use than it needs to be.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying another organiser, basket, shelf, trolley or storage container, it is worth
    slowing down and checking what problem you are actually trying to solve.
  </p>
  <p>
    A good kitchen storage product should make daily use easier. It should not simply move
    clutter from one place to another.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide walks through what to measure, what to check, and what to think about before
    buying kitchen storage for a house, unit, townhouse, apartment or rental.
  </p>

  <h2>Our take</h2>
  <p>
    Kitchen storage works best when it solves a specific problem.
  </p>
  <p>
    A drawer divider can help if utensils are tangled together. A pull-out pantry organiser
    may help if food disappears at the back of a deep cupboard. Stackable containers can make
    sense if packets are collapsing and spilling through the pantry.
  </p>
  <p>
    But buying storage before understanding the problem can make the kitchen more frustrating.
    Too many containers, baskets and organisers can take up space, add extra steps, and make
    the kitchen harder to maintain.
  </p>
  <p>The better starting point is simple:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Identify the problem.</li>
    <li>Measure the space.</li>
    <li>Check how the kitchen is used each day.</li>
    <li>Choose storage that reduces friction.</li>
    <li>Avoid products that only look organised when empty.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Match the starting point to the problem</h2>
  <p>
    Different kitchen problems need different solutions. Before buying anything, match the
    product to the actual issue.
  </p>
  <div class="advice-stack">
    <section>
      <h3>If bench space is limited</h3>
      <p>
        Prioritise tools and storage that can live in drawers, cupboards, wall-mounted spaces
        or appliance garages before buying another benchtop appliance. A clear bench is often
        more helpful than another item sitting permanently on it.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>If the kitchen is a small rental</h3>
      <p>
        Choose removable storage, compact cookware and items that do not need drilling,
        permanent fixing or landlord approval. Freestanding shelves, tension rods, over-door
        racks and drawer organisers may be more suitable than fixed cabinetry.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>If containers are the problem</h3>
      <p>
        Keep containers that stack neatly, seal properly and have matching lids. Remove odd
        pieces that no longer close, no longer stack or no longer suit the way the household
        stores food.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>If drawers are full of gadgets</h3>
      <p>
        Keep the tools used weekly. Avoid single-purpose gadgets unless they solve a frequent
        problem. A drawer full of rarely used tools usually needs editing before it needs more
        dividers.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>If pantry items are hard to find</h3>
      <p>
        The answer may be grouping and visibility rather than more storage. Clear containers,
        shallow baskets and turntables can help, but only if they make everyday items easier
        to see and reach.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h3>If cupboards are deep and awkward</h3>
      <p>
        Pull-out organisers, tiered shelves or labelled baskets may help bring items forward.
        The goal is to reduce forgotten items at the back, not to fill every spare centimetre.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <h2>What to measure before buying kitchen storage</h2>
  <p>
    Measuring first prevents most storage mistakes. Kitchen organisers often fail because they
    technically fit inside a cupboard but do not work once doors, hinges, pipes, handles,
    shelf lips or appliance cords are considered.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying, measure the actual usable space.
  </p>

  <h3>Cupboard width, depth and height</h3>
  <p>Measure inside the cupboard, not the outside of the cabinet.</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Internal width from side to side.</li>
    <li>Internal depth from front to back.</li>
    <li>Usable height between shelves.</li>
    <li>Whether the shelf is adjustable.</li>
    <li>Whether hinges reduce the usable opening.</li>
    <li>Whether door frames or lips block wider organisers.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A storage basket may fit on the shelf but still be hard to remove if the cupboard opening
    is narrower than the internal space.
  </p>

  <h3>Drawer depth and internal width</h3>
  <p>For drawer organisers, measure the inside of the drawer.</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Drawer width.</li>
    <li>Drawer depth.</li>
    <li>Drawer height.</li>
    <li>Whether the drawer sides curve inward.</li>
    <li>Whether the organiser blocks the drawer from closing.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Some bamboo or expandable organisers look flexible but still need enough internal
    clearance to open and close properly.
  </p>

  <h3>Pantry shelf spacing</h3>
  <p>
    Pantries often have tall gaps that waste vertical space or short gaps that make stacking
    difficult. Measure the height between shelves, the depth of each shelf, the width of the
    pantry opening, whether containers can be removed easily and whether baskets will scrape
    against the shelf above.
  </p>
  <p>
    If shelves are adjustable, changing the shelf height may solve part of the problem before
    buying anything.
  </p>

  <h3>Appliance clearance</h3>
  <p>Small kitchen appliances can be deceptively awkward to store.</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Check appliance height.</li>
    <li>Check cupboard height.</li>
    <li>Measure appliance depth including handles or cords.</li>
    <li>Consider whether it is too heavy to lift down safely.</li>
    <li>Check whether it needs ventilation when in use.</li>
    <li>Ask whether it will realistically be used if stored high up.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A heavy appliance stored above shoulder height is not convenient storage. It is often just
    delayed frustration.
  </p>

  <h3>Fridge and door clearance</h3>
  <p>
    Slim trolleys and side-of-fridge storage can be useful in some kitchens, but only if they
    do not block movement. Check fridge door swing, pantry door swing, walkway width, handle
    clearance, whether drawers or doors can still open fully and whether the trolley would be
    stable on the floor surface.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not assume narrow spaces are automatically useful storage spaces.
  </p>

  <h3>Sink and under-bench obstacles</h3>
  <p>
    Under-sink storage needs extra care because of pipes, hoses and moisture. Check pipe
    location, water filter location if present, bin clearance, cleaning product height, shelf
    depth and signs of leaks or dampness.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid storing items that may be damaged by moisture under the sink.
  </p>

  <h2>What to check before buying</h2>
  <p>
    Once you know the measurements, check whether the product suits the way the kitchen is
    actually used.
  </p>

  <h3>Will it make daily use easier?</h3>
  <p>
    Good storage reduces effort. Ask whether it will make items easier to reach, reduce
    clutter, save time, make sense to everyone in the household and still work when full.
  </p>
  <p>
    If a storage item only looks good when carefully arranged, it may not survive daily use.
  </p>

  <h3>Is it easy to clean?</h3>
  <p>
    Kitchen storage needs to handle crumbs, oil, spills and dust. Before buying, check for
    smooth surfaces, removable parts, washable materials, corners that do not trap crumbs and
    finishes that suit kitchen use.
  </p>
  <p>
    Wire baskets, fabric bins and timber organisers can all work, but they suit different
    jobs. Food storage areas need to be especially easy to wipe down.
  </p>

  <h3>Does it suit renters?</h3>
  <p>
    Renters should be careful with anything that needs screws, adhesive strips, wall mounting
    or cabinet modification.
  </p>
  <p>
    Look for freestanding storage, removable drawer organisers, tension-mounted options,
    over-door racks that do not damage doors, non-permanent shelf inserts and compact products
    that can move to another home.
  </p>
  <p>
    Adhesive products may still damage paint or cabinet finishes when removed, so check the
    surface before committing.
  </p>

  <h3>Does it create extra steps?</h3>
  <p>
    Some storage systems look tidy but make cooking harder. Decanting every pantry item into
    containers may look organised, but it also requires washing, refilling, labelling and
    tracking expiry dates.
  </p>
  <p>
    That may suit some households. It may be annoying in others. Before buying, ask whether
    the system matches the effort you are willing to maintain.
  </p>

  <h3>Does it work with what you already own?</h3>
  <p>
    Storage should match existing cookware, containers, pantry items and appliances. Check
    plate sizes, pot and pan handles, container shapes, spice jar sizes, packet heights,
    appliance dimensions, bin sizes and cleaning product sizes.
  </p>
  <p>
    Buying storage without checking existing items can lead to organisers that technically fit
    the cupboard but do not fit the things you actually use.
  </p>

  <h2>Product types that may help</h2>
  <p>
    The right product depends on the problem. These are common kitchen storage categories and
    when they may be worth considering.
  </p>

  <h3>Drawer dividers</h3>
  <p>
    Drawer dividers can help with cutlery, utensils, wraps, food bags, measuring spoons and
    small tools. They suit drawers where items are loose and tangled. They are less helpful if
    the drawer simply contains too many rarely used items.
  </p>

  <h3>Stackable food containers</h3>
  <p>
    Stackable containers can help if pantry packets are collapsing, spilling or hiding behind
    one another. They work best when they are easy to open, easy to clean and used for foods
    that are regularly refilled.
  </p>
  <p>
    Avoid buying large container sets before checking what foods you actually store and how
    much space the containers require when empty.
  </p>

  <h3>Clear pantry bins</h3>
  <p>
    Clear bins can group similar items such as snacks, baking supplies, breakfast items or
    lunchbox goods. They are useful for deep shelves because the whole group can be pulled
    forward. They are less useful if they become a place to hide unrelated items.
  </p>

  <h3>Tiered shelves</h3>
  <p>
    Tiered shelves can help with spices, cans and small jars. They improve visibility,
    especially in shallow cupboards. They may not suit deep pantry shelves if items at the
    back are still hard to reach.
  </p>

  <h3>Pull-out organisers</h3>
  <p>
    Pull-out organisers can help in deep cupboards or lower cabinets where items are difficult
    to access. They are usually more involved than simple baskets, so check measurements
    carefully. For renters, avoid anything that requires permanent installation unless
    approval is clear.
  </p>

  <h3>Lazy Susans and turntables</h3>
  <p>
    Turntables can help with oils, sauces, spreads, spices or small pantry items. They work
    best when there is enough clearance around the sides and above the items. They are less
    useful for square packets or large containers that waste the circular space.
  </p>

  <h3>Over-door storage</h3>
  <p>
    Over-door racks can add storage to pantry doors or cupboard doors. They may help with
    wraps, cleaning supplies, small jars or lightweight pantry items. Check door thickness,
    hinge clearance and whether the rack prevents the door from closing properly.
  </p>

  <h3>Slim trolleys</h3>
  <p>
    Slim trolleys can use narrow spaces beside fridges, benches or pantries. They can be
    useful, but only if the trolley remains stable, accessible and does not block walkways.
    Avoid overloading narrow trolleys with heavy bottles or breakable items.
  </p>

  <h3>Under-shelf baskets</h3>
  <p>
    Under-shelf baskets can use the empty space below shelves. They may help with wraps,
    lightweight packets or small items. Check shelf thickness and whether the basket reduces
    the usable space below it.
  </p>

  <h2>Common mistakes to avoid</h2>
  <p>
    Kitchen storage can create new problems when it is bought too quickly.
  </p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>
      <strong>Buying organisers before measuring:</strong> a product can look suitable online
      but fail because of a hinge, pipe, shelf lip, drawer curve or door handle.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Filling every empty space:</strong> a kitchen needs breathing room so items can
      be removed, cleaned and returned easily.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Buying too many matching containers:</strong> large sets take up space, need
      washing, require labels and may not suit every pantry item.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Ignoring maintenance:</strong> if the household is unlikely to keep up with
      labels, decanting or strict zones, choose simpler storage.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Choosing style over function:</strong> prioritise access, cleaning, durability
      and fit before colour, finish or matching sets.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Forgetting about renters:</strong> permanent shelves, adhesive racks and
      drilled fixtures can be risky in rentals.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Keeping too many duplicates:</strong> if the drawer has six spatulas, four
      peelers or several unused gadgets, a new organiser may not solve the problem.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Fit by household type</h2>
  <p>
    Different households need different kitchen storage choices.
  </p>

  <h3>For renters</h3>
  <p>
    Look for storage that can move with you: drawer dividers, freestanding shelves, removable
    pantry bins, compact containers, tension rods, over-door racks and slim trolleys. Be
    cautious with adhesive hooks, wall-mounted rails and anything that may damage cabinet
    finishes.
  </p>

  <h3>For families</h3>
  <p>
    Family kitchens need storage that is easy to understand and easy to reset. Visible pantry
    zones, snack baskets, lunchbox storage, durable containers, easy-access drawers and simple
    labels can help. Avoid systems that rely on everyone following a complicated layout.
  </p>

  <h3>For small apartments</h3>
  <p>
    Small kitchens need compact, flexible storage: nesting cookware, stackable containers,
    narrow drawer organisers, wall-friendly removable storage, multi-use tools, fewer
    duplicate appliances and storage that keeps benches clear. The aim is to make the kitchen
    easier to use, not to squeeze in as much as possible.
  </p>

  <h3>For busy households</h3>
  <p>
    Busy households need storage that reduces decisions. Group items by task, keep daily tools
    within easy reach, store occasional items higher or further away and avoid systems that
    need constant re-labelling or rearranging. If a system takes too long to reset, it
    probably will not last.
  </p>

  <h2>When not to buy anything yet</h2>
  <p>
    Sometimes the best first step is not buying storage. You may not need to buy anything yet
    if the main issue is expired pantry food, duplicate utensils, containers without lids,
    lids without containers, unused appliances, gadgets kept just in case, cookware that does
    not fit the stove or household, poor grouping of items, or items stored far from where
    they are used.
  </p>
  <p>
    In those cases, remove and regroup first. A cupboard with fewer items may work better
    without any new products.
  </p>

  <h2>A kitchen storage checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying kitchen storage, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>What exact problem am I solving?</li>
    <li>Have I measured the usable space?</li>
    <li>Will this fit around hinges, handles, doors, shelves and pipes?</li>
    <li>Will I use this every week?</li>
    <li>Is it easy to clean?</li>
    <li>Is it suitable for a rental if needed?</li>
    <li>Does it make daily use easier?</li>
    <li>Does it work with what I already own?</li>
    <li>Will it still work when full?</li>
    <li>Would decluttering solve the problem first?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Kitchen storage does not need to be complicated. The most useful changes are often simple:
    fewer duplicates, better grouping, clearer access and products that fit the actual space.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure first, buy slowly, and choose storage that makes the kitchen easier to use every
    day.
  </p>

